gomodel:SYNGO_355  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Vesicular aminergic-associated transporter (Slc10a4) is co-localized with synaptic vesicles positive for VAChT and VMAT2 as show by STED microscopy and in situ proximity ligation assay (Fig. 1 F-I). Immunoblotting of purified synaptic vesicles for VAChT, VMAT2 and VAAT confirm VAAT-localization to SVs (Fig. 4 C).\nThis observation is supported by co-localization analysis of Slc10a4 with VAChT and VMAT2 in mouse striatum and spinal cord, Fig. S1 H-I and S1 J-K, respectively. A biochemical support for these findings is shown in Fig. S1 O (immunoisolation of transporter-positive vesicles followed by Western blot detection).\nAdditionally, association of the transporter with SVs at symmetrical synapses is assessed by immunogold labelling (electron microscopy, see Fig. S1 L).\n\nImmunohistochemistry experiments on adult mouse brain sections (Fig. S1 B-F) and on human brain samples (Fig. S1 G) confirm distribution of the protein in brain regions containing cholinergic, dopaminergic or serotonergic neurons. The data is supported by RNA in situ hybridization experiments detecting slc10a4 RNA in cholinergic and monoaminergic regions of mouse CNS (Fig 1A-E).\n\n4/9/2017 Pim\n- Based on the known transmembrane topology of the protein, the \"integral component of ... membrane\" term was chosen.. Experimental description: Synaptic vesicle preparations (M&M):\nVesicles used for STED and in situ PLA were purified using a hybrid of existing protocols allowing increase purity of SV and described in detail elsewhere (Ahmed S, Holt M, Riedel D, Jahn R. (2013): Small-scale isolation of synaptic vesicles from mammalian brain. Nat Protoc. 8(5):998-1009).\nIn the figure legend of Fig. S1 as well as in the \"tissue preparation for histology\" text (M&M section )in the supplementary material, the authors indicate that adult mice were used.\n\nPlease note that in this reference publication, the authors use also rat and human tissue samples for their experiments. However, I referred only to the figures showing results from mouse-derived biological material." , "Automated change 2024-03-14: GO:0030285 replaced by GO:0030672" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1542-3498" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3898-5197" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0808-7003" ;
        dc:date           "2024-03-14" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_355" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

